      <item>
        <title>Problem with partitioning</title>
        <dc:creator><![CDATA[@billygotshot billygotshot]]></dc:creator>
        <description><![CDATA[
          <p><a href="https://forum.moparisthebest.com/u/billygotshot">@billygotshot</a> wrote:</p>
          <blockquote>
              <aside class="quote no-group quote-modified" data-post="3" data-topic="207302">
<div class="title">
<div class="quote-controls"></div>
<img alt width="20" height="20" src="https://forum.moparisthebest.com/user_avatar/forum.moparisthebest.com/mopman/40/33_1.png" class="avatar"> Mopman:</div>
<blockquote>
<p>You don’t need to format the partition, just create some free space in gparted (shrink your other partition or whatever) and then tell windows to install on the free space. It will create the partition itself and format it as NTFS (or FAT32 if you really wish)</p>
</blockquote>
</aside>
<p>I have tried that already. my xp disk won’t let me lol.</p>
<aside class="quote no-group" data-post="4" data-topic="207302">
<div class="title">
<div class="quote-controls"></div>
<img alt width="20" height="20" src="https://forum.moparisthebest.com/letter_avatar/rictoo/40/5_6bca9977b612b7aeef77ba1ec1cd67b3.png" class="avatar"> Rictoo:</div>
<blockquote>
<p>Use cfdisk to partition (set the partition to id 7), and mkfs.ntfs to make the filesystem.</p>
</blockquote>
</aside>
<p>I will try that.</p>
          </blockquote>
          <p><a href="https://forum.moparisthebest.com/t/problem-with-partitioning/207302/5">Read full topic</a></p>
        ]]></description>
